huntYears.NOTES:
IMPORTANT! PLEASE READ
Crown Castle, in partnership with the U.S. Forest Service, is installing fiber optics and cell towers in American Fork Canyon between Tibble Fork Reservoir and Silver Lake Flat. The project will improve communications and enhance safety for canyon visitors.
To complete this work, Forest Road 008 to Silver Lake Flat will close on Monday, August 1, and reopen in late September.
The roads to Tibble Fork Reservoir, Granite Flat Campground and Mineral Basin will remain open, as well as the surrounding trail network. Hunters should expect limited access to Silver Lake Flat as well as heavy equipment and crews working on Forest Road 008. All visitors should follow the posted signage and use extreme caution when hiking trails that cross through the construction zone.

huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
Land Ownership: Moose habitat is primarily public land.

Population Objective: 500

Current Population Estimate: 350
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: Always be sure of your target. Don't shoot from roads. Do not keep a loaded gun in your vehicle
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season. Be prepared for rain, lightening, snow, wind and heat. It is quite common on clear mornings for clouds to build through the morning and have thunderstorms in the afternoon. Be very cautious of lightening while hunting on high ridges. Early fall snow storms occur regularly in this area. Most years the snow will melt off, within a day or two until through the first week on October.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Scouting Tips: Most moose are seen near rivers, streams, ponds, or lakes, focus your efforts near these areas. Later in the fall they will move into thick, brushy areas of oak brush and mahogany. Moose are very spread out on these subunits, so it is important to cover a lot of area. It is a great place to camp in the summer to scout and learn the roads and trails. Behavior: As with most big game animals the early mornings and evenings are the best times to find moose. This is when most rutting activity will take place as well. Moose are typically a solitary animals.

Recommended areas Wasatch West Subunit: American Fork Canyon- The canyon road takes you from the mouth of AF canyon east to Heber City. This area has a lot of moose. Look around Casacade Springs area. Strawberry Reservoir- Look along all streams feeding into Strawberry Reservoir, such as Strawberry River, Coop Creek, Mud Creek and Indian Creek and Trout Creek. These areas are not a high density area. Salt Lake County- All canyons on the east side of the valley have moose in them, such as Big and Little Cottonwood Canyons, Mill Creek, and Lambs Canyon. You can hunt with any weapon east on I-15 for cow moose. Other canyons to look in- Squaw Peak road, Right Hand Fork of Hobble Creek, Diamond Fork, Sheep Creek and Tie Fork. Not a lot of moose in these areas.

Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites. Ashley National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/uwcnf

huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Salt Lake, Summit, Utah and Wasatch counties—Boundary begins at I-80 and I-15 in Salt Lake City; east on I-80 to US-40; south on US-40 to SR-32; east on SR-32 to SR-35 at Francis: southeast on SR-35 to the USFS Road 054 (Mill Hollow road); southwest on this road to the USFS Road 083 (Lake Creek road); southeast on USFS Road 83 to USFS Road 82 (new Co-op Creek road); south on USFS Road 82 to US-40; east on US-40 to the USFS Road 090 (Soldier Creek Dam road); south on this road to the Soldier Creek Dam and the Strawberry River; southeast along this river to Beaver Creek; southwest along this creek to Big Beaver Spring and the USFS Road 081 (Reservation Ridge road); southeast on this road to the Right Fork of White River road; southwest on this road to US-6; northwest on US-6 to I-15; north on I-15 to I-80 in Salt Lake City. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Duchesne, Nephi, Provo, Salt Lake City. Boundary questions? Call the Springville office, (801) 491-5678.
